{{Campaignbox First Indochina War}}
On December 19, 1946 [[Vietnam]]ese Viet Minh soldiers detonated explosives in [[Hanoi]], and the ensuing battle, known as the '''Battle of Hanoi''' marked the opening salvo of the [[First Indochina War]]. The explosives, set off at 20:03 in the evening, had been smuggled past [[French Army]] guards into the city's power plant. The result explosion plunged Hanoi into darkness, and throughout the city the [[Viet-Minh]] began attacking French military positions and French homes.<ref name="Bradley2009">{{cite book|last=Bradley|first=Mark Philip|title=Vietnam at war|date=2009-05-15|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-280349-8|page=47}}<!--|accessdate=19 May 2010--></ref> Surviving French troops, alerted by friendly spies, gradually gained a numerical superiority. French artillery shelled the city, and house to house searches were conducted searching for the Viet-Minh leadership.

Ho Chi Minh was at the time ill with fever, and [[Vo Nguyen Giap]] ordered "all soldiers... to stand together, go into battle, destroy the invaders, and save the nation." Eventual French superiority in firepower forced the Viet-Minh to withdraw to mountains 80 miles to the north of the Hanoi.<ref name="Vo2006">{{cite book|last=Vo|first=Nghia M.|title=The Vietnamese boat people, 1954 and 1975-1992|year=2006|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-2345-3|page=13}}<!--|accessdate=19 May 2010--></ref> However, it took the French 60 days to gain complete control of the city, which had bought enough time for their enemy to evacuate all of its central offices, as well as most of its main forces.{{fact|date=September 2013}} After expunging the Viet-Minh from the city, the French demanded the military surrender of their opponents, but the latter refused. The [[United States]], alarmed at the incident, dispatched [[Abbot Low Moffat]] on a special mission to [[Saigon]] and Hanoi to consider a negotiated referendum. However, the realization that the Viet-Minh would not accept compromise led to the US abandoning the idea.<ref name="Schulzinger1998">{{cite book|last=Schulzinger|first=Robert D.|title=A time for war: the United States and Vietnam, 1941-1975|date=1998-12-01|publisher=Oxford University Press US|isbn=978-0-19-512501-6|pages=28–31}}<!--|accessdate=19 May 2010--></ref>

